it.jupiter assertions. I think I should be using assertThat for better clarity in my tests. Let's make these adjustments and see how it goes!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Considering compiler setup**\\n\\nI’m thinking about how the runtime compiler might be in a native image and that the build likely has a compiler ready for macro compilation. It seems I should use the compiler — that part is good! I wonder if I need a package with an underscore, considering how Scala handles public top-level objects. In Scala, objects include a `$` when compiled, but the file or class name doesn’t. Alright, let’s get to writing!\"}]}"}, {"type": "toolCall", "id": "call_6rLm4wH564JQDgm7cDCHbfe6|fc_0a26ca532b5f0766016a400c4403708194a0cb83dbb59615f1", "name": "write", "arguments": {"path": "tests/src/dev.zio/izumi-reflect_2.13/2.3.8/src/test/scala/dev_zio/izumi_reflect_2_13/LightTypeTagImplTest.scala", "content": "/*\n * Copyright and related rights waived via CC0\n *\n * You should have received a copy of the CC0 legalcode along with this\n * work. If not, see <http://creativecommons.org/publicdomain/zero/1.0/>.\n */\npackage dev_zio.izumi_reflect_2_13\n\nimport izumi.reflect.macrortti.LightTypeTag\nimport izumi.reflect.macrortti.LightTypeTagImpl\nimport org.assertj.core.api.Assertions.assertThat\nimport org.junit.jupiter.api.Test\n\nimport scala.reflect.runtime.universe\n\nclass LightTypeTagImplTest {\n  @Test\n  def buildsRuntimeTagForNestedTypeWithStableValuePrefix(): Unit = {\n    val tag: LightTypeTag = LightTypeTagImpl.makeLightTypeTag(universe)(\n      universe.typeOf[LightTypeTagImplFixtures.StableModule.Inner]\n    )\n\n    assertThat(tag.ref.longNameWithPrefix).contains(\"StableModule\")\n    assertThat(tag.ref.longNameWithPrefix).contains(\"Inner\")\n    assertThat(tag.serialize().ref).isNotBlank\n  }\n}\n\nobject LightTypeTagImplFixtures {\n  object StableModule {\n    final class Inner\n  }\n}\n"}}], "api": "openai-responses", "provider": "OCA", "model": "o